{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"3\n    \n      ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n      Hybrid — Mode Switcher inside shared shell\n      One URL (/modules/lld). On first visit, shell shows a compact \"How do you want to start?\" banner with 3 modes: Learn / Build / Drill. Pick one — content pane switches. Mode switcher stays visible at top. Returning users land on last-used mode. Same shell, 3 content modes inside.\n\n      \n      \n        SHARED SHELL · mode switcher at top · content pane swaps below\n\n        \n        \n          \n          LLD · Singleton\n          \n          \n            Learn\n            Build\n            Drill\n          \n        \n\n        \n        \n          \n            CANVAS (auto-highlights as you scroll)\n            \n              [Singleton UML · class highlighted]\n            \n          \n          \n            LESSON COLUMN (scroll-synced)\n            \n              Why Singleton?\n              Imagine a thread-safe logger... Everyone writes to the same file.\n              \n                ✓ Checkpoint: What makes Singleton thread-unsafe?\n              \n            \n          \n        \n\n        \n          ↓ Switch to Build → same URL, canvas becomes full-width with sidebar · Switch to Drill → problem queue appears\n        \n      \n\n      \n        \n          Pros\n          \n            Preserves current Build mode untouched\n            Ship incrementally — add Learn first, Drill later\n            One URL = SEO / sharing stays simple\n            Mode switcher = persona C can jump to Drill instantly\n            First-visit banner = picks their path without force-gate\n            Remembers last mode = returning user feels personal\n          \n        \n        \n          Cons\n          \n            Shell complexity grows — must handle 3 modes\n            Learn and Build fight over canvas real estate\n            \"Smart defaults\" tuning takes iteration\n          \n        \n      \n      \n        Effort: 🟢 Medium (3-4 weeks, shippable in 2 phases) · Risk: Low · Future flex: High","choice":"3","id":null,"timestamp":1776637839468}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"3\n    \n      ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n      Hybrid — Mode Switcher inside shared shell\n      One URL (/modules/lld). On first visit, shell shows a compact \"How do you want to start?\" banner with 3 modes: Learn / Build / Drill. Pick one — content pane switches. Mode switcher stays visible at top. Returning users land on last-used mode. Same shell, 3 content modes inside.\n\n      \n      \n        SHARED SHELL · mode switcher at top · content pane swaps below\n\n        \n        \n          \n          LLD · Singleton\n          \n          \n            Learn\n            Build\n            Drill\n          \n        \n\n        \n        \n          \n            CANVAS (auto-highlights as you scroll)\n            \n              [Singleton UML · class highlighted]\n            \n          \n          \n            LESSON COLUMN (scroll-synced)\n            \n              Why Singleton?\n              Imagine a thread-safe logger... Everyone writes to the same file.\n              \n                ✓ Checkpoint: What makes Singleton thread-unsafe?\n              \n            \n          \n        \n\n        \n          ↓ Switch to Build → same URL, canvas becomes full-width with sidebar · Switch to Drill → problem queue appears\n        \n      \n\n      \n        \n          Pros\n          \n            Preserves current Build mode untouched\n            Ship incrementally — add Learn first, Drill later\n            One URL = SEO / sharing stays simple\n            Mode switcher = persona C can jump to Drill instantly\n            First-visit banner = picks their path without force-gate\n            Remembers last mode = returning user feels personal\n          \n        \n        \n          Cons\n          \n            Shell complexity grows — must handle 3 modes\n            Learn and Build fight over canvas real estate\n            \"Smart defaults\" tuning takes iteration\n          \n        \n      \n    