{"type":"screen-added","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/12-q02-learning-path.html"}
{"type":"screen-updated","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/12-q02-learning-path.html"}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"D\n    \n      ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n      Hybrid · recommended path (DAG) + \"free explore\" escape hatch\n      Default view shows a curated learning path — 36 patterns ordered in a DAG, highlighted node = \"start here\", next node = \"suggested next\". But nothing is locked. A toggle [Guided · All patterns] swaps to flat list for pros.\n\n      \n      \n        \n          Guided path\n          All 36 patterns\n        \n        \n          ✓\n          Singleton — OOP gateway pattern\n          ▶\n          Factory Method ← RECOMMENDED NEXT\n          ○\n          Builder — complex object construction\n          ○\n          Abstract Factory — families of factories\n          ○\n          Observer — pub-sub within a process\n          ○\n          Strategy — swappable algorithms\n          …\n          31 more · click to jump\n        \n      \n\n      \n        Pros: Persona A follows path. Persona B follows path but jumps if bored. Persona C clicks \"All patterns\" once, never sees guided view again. All served.\n        Cons: Authoring the DAG still requires thought (but you don't enforce it, so mistakes cost less). Two UI states to maintain.","choice":"d","id":null,"timestamp":1776640055425}
