     \n      \n        Next-action row (tiered): 90+ shows \"Next problem →\"; 70-89 shows \"Retry · Next problem\"; 50-69 shows \"Review this pattern · Retry\"; <50 shows \"Open Learn mode · See reference solution\".\n      \n\n      \n        Pros: Celebration is earned. Failure is coached. Pros get specifics, beginners get paths forward. 3-second choreography feels intentional, not patronizing.\n        Cons: More component surface (4 tiered reveals vs 1 generic). ~5-8h extra.","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1776641742461}
{"type":"screen-added","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/21-q11-cross-mode.html"}
{"type":"screen-updated","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/21-q11-cross-mode.html"}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n    \n      ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n      Smart boundaries · work persists, UI state discards\n      The policy the table above implements: work (canvas, progress, timer, scroll) persists to DB. Transient UI (dropdowns, half-typed inputs) discards. Ambiguous cases (unsaved tinker, mid-submit) get explicit confirmation.\n      \n        Pros: User trust — never silently loses work, never uncanny-resumes random UI. Explicit confirmation for edge cases respects user agency. Storage-efficient.\n        Cons: 3 dialogs possible (tinker save, drill mid-submit, drill grade). Must be designed well to not be annoying.","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1776641896023}
{"type":"screen-added","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/22-q12-drill-start.html"}
{"type":"screen-updated","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/22-q12-drill-start.html"}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C\n    \n      ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n      User picks at drill start · 3 modes per problem\n      When user clicks a problem, modal asks:\n\n      \n        Design Parking Lot · how do you want to start?\n        \n          \n            \n              🎯\n              \n                Interview mode · blank canvas DEFAULT\n                Requirements + timer. Design from scratch. Realistic.\n              \n            \n          \n          \n            \n              🚂\n              \n                Guided mode · starter classes\n                Pre-populated skeleton · fill in methods + relationships. Lower stakes.\n              \n            \n          \n          \n            \n              ⚡\n              \n                Speed mode · starter + no timer\n                Pure practice. No pressure. Grade records as \"practice\", not in SRS stats.\n              \n            \n          \n        \n      \n\n      \n        Pros: User autonomy. First-time users pick Guided; crammers default to Interview. Speed mode is a welcome \"untimed practice\" option no competitor offers. All 3 use same grading engine.\n        Cons: One extra click before drill starts. Solved by remembering user's default choice.","choice":"c","id":null,"timestamp":1776642151300}
{"type":"screen-added","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/23-q13-gamification.html"}
