{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C\n    \n      ⭐ MY RECOMMENDATION\n      Smart hybrid · auto-merge when safe, confirm when conflicting\n      Server runs a 3-case decision tree on login:\n\n      \n\n        \n          CASE 1 · localStorage has data, DB empty (S1 · first sign-up)\n          Silent auto-merge. Welcome toast: \"Welcome! Your 5 patterns of progress have been saved to your account.\" No decision asked — clearly the right move.\n        \n\n        \n          CASE 2 · localStorage AND DB both have data (S2 · conflict)\n          \n            Confirmation dialog.\n            \"We found 5 patterns you worked on in this browser, and 12 patterns saved to your account. What would you like to do?\"\n            [Keep account · merge this browser's patterns if any are newer]\n            [Discard browser progress]\n          \n        \n\n        \n          CASE 3 · localStorage empty OR DB has everything (S3 · clean)\n          Nothing to do. Just log in. No toast needed.\n        \n      \n\n      \n      \n        CONFLICT RESOLUTION · \"KEEP ACCOUNT · MERGE IF NEWER\"\n        \n          For each pattern:\n          \n            If DB has progress but localStorage doesn't → DB wins (no change)\n            If localStorage has progress but DB doesn't → local wins (insert to DB)\n            If both have progress → higher completion tier wins (mastered > completed > introduced)\n            For equal tiers, latest `updatedAt` wins\n          \n        \n      \n\n      \n        Pros: Never loses work without consent. Clear UX for each scenario. Smart merge rules (tier-based, not timestamp-only) preserve progress. S2 risk eliminated.\n        Cons: 3 code paths to maintain. The merge algorithm needs careful testing for conflict case.","choice":"c","id":null,"timestamp":1776642833536}
