{"type":"screen-updated","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/33-batch2-motion.html"}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"M1\n    \n      Pattern signature animations · each pattern has a unique micro-motion\n      When you open a pattern, the UML classes perform a pattern-specific motion that embodies the pattern's essence. This becomes a visual mnemonic — you can recognize a pattern by the way its classes arrange.\n      \n        \n          🧘 Singleton — one class pulses gently at center, alone\n        \n        \n          📢 Observer — subject emits waves toward subscribers\n        \n        \n          🏭 Factory Method — Creator \"produces\" concrete products cascading down\n        \n        \n          ⚡ Circuit Breaker — edge pulses, then snaps/blocks on failure threshold\n        \n        \n          🔧 Strategy — concrete strategies slide in/out of context slot\n        \n        \n          🧅 Decorator — wrappers nest around core class like rings\n        \n      \n      36 patterns × 3-5s animation. Can be AI-scripted via motion.dev keyframes. Plays once on pattern open; optional \"replay\" button. Respects reduced-motion. ~25-30h across all 36 (templates reduce per-pattern to ~45min each).","choice":"m1","id":null,"timestamp":1776643956719}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"M2\n    \n      Runtime particle flow · \"watch the pattern actually run\"\n      Inspired by your existing ParticleLayer in System Design. A \"▶ Play\" button on the canvas simulates the pattern at runtime — particles flow through the class graph representing method calls. Observer's notify() sends particles from subject to each subscriber simultaneously. Chain of Responsibility passes a single particle hop-by-hop until it stops. You see the pattern execute.\n      \n        Subject\n        ObsA\n        ObsB\n        \n        \n        \n        \n        notify() fanout as particles → reaches ObsA, ObsB\n      \n      Each pattern needs a runtime trace script (like stage directions). ~20h infra + ~10h total for 36 pattern scripts. Unique-to-Architex feature. Viral demo material.","choice":"m2","id":null,"timestamp":1776644022115}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"M3\n    \n      Progressive class reveal · classes appear as lesson introduces them\n      Opening Learn mode: canvas starts near-empty. As you scroll through the lesson and it introduces each class, that class fades in + scales up on the canvas. By the time you finish the lesson, the complete UML has been built alongside you, not just presented.\n      Leverages Q7's highlightedClassIds — extend to visibleClassIds. Scroll position drives reveal. Motion: opacity 0→1, scale 0.9→1, 400ms ease-out with gentle stagger. ~6h.","choice":"m3","id":null,"timestamp":1776644029482}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"M4\n    \n      Magnetic hover · related classes glow together\n      Hover any class → it + all structurally-connected classes (via inheritance, composition, etc.) get a subtle shared glow. Non-connected classes dim to 40%. Reveals the pattern's structural \"neighborhood\" at a glance.\n      Your codebase already has \"focus mode\" (hover dims unrelated). This extends it: connected classes get an additional accent glow, not just kept-bright. ~3h polish on existing.","choice":"m4","id":null,"timestamp":1776644034040}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"M5\n    \n      Mode-switch choreography · crossfade + spatial transition\n      Clicking Learn → Build → Drill → Review currently swaps content instantly. Propose: 300ms transition — old content fades + slides out direction of target mode, new content fades in from opposite. Subtle but gives modes a spatial relationship in muscle memory (Learn feels \"left of\" Build, Drill \"right of\" Build).\n      Motion library handles this. Direction derived from mode index delta. Respects reduced-motion (fall back to instant crossfade). ~4h.","choice":"m5","id":null,"timestamp":1776644034577}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"M6\n    \n      Tinker unlock · ceremonial permission moment\n      Clicking \"Tinker\" in Learn mode should feel deliberate. Canvas briefly shimmers (gradient sweep across classes), class borders shift from solid to dashed (indicating editable state), toolbar slides down from top. Makes entering tinker mode feel like unlocking something, not just enabling a flag.\n      ~3h for the shimmer + border transition + toolbar slide.","choice":"m6","id":null,"timestamp":1776644035643}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"M7\n    \n      Drill timer · heartbeat on last 5 minutes\n      Timer ticks silently for 20 min. At 5:00 remaining, it starts subtly pulsing — then at 1:00 remaining, the pulse speeds up slightly. Never hostile, just tonally urgent. Creates micro-tension at the right moments.\n      CSS keyframe + setInterval to set phase. ~2h.","choice":"m7","id":null,"timestamp":1776644036390}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"M8\n    \n      Ambient canvas breathing · subtle idle motion\n      When canvas is idle (no user interaction for 10s), existing ambient particles (already in your codebase!) drift more noticeably. When user touches canvas → particles recede. Signals \"alive vs active\" states without being distracting.\n      Tune existing lld-particle-drift animation opacity based on interaction timer. ~2h.","choice":"m8","id":null,"timestamp":1776644036973}
{"type":"screen-added","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/34-batch3-content.html"}
{"type":"screen-updated","file":"/Users/a0g11b6/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-WalmartInc/Desktop/my_projects/architex/.superpowers/brainstorm/64431-1776636958/content/34-batch3-content.html"}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C1\n    \n      Interactive code playground · edit code → UML auto-updates\n      Bottom of lesson column gets a live Monaco editor. User edits the TS code sample — adds a method, removes a class — and the UML canvas reflects the change in real-time. Leverages your existing code-to-diagram.ts bidirectional sync (already 707 lines, working).\n      \n        \n          \n            CODE (editable)\n            \n              class Logger {\n                private static instance;\n                private constructor()\n                static getInstance() {}\n              }\n            \n          \n          \n            UML (auto-synced)\n            \n              Logger⚡ updates live\n            \n          \n        \n      \n      Killer feature. Uses existing infrastructure. \"Write code, see structure\" is the exact loop engineers need. ~12-15h to polish into lesson column.","choice":"c1","id":null,"timestamp":1776644172520}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C2\n    \n      Anti-pattern museum · \"here's what breaks without this pattern\"\n      Each pattern page has a toggle: \"See the 'before' version\". Shows the naïve wrong approach — nested constructors for Builder, giant switch statement for State, tight coupling for Observer. Side-by-side with the pattern-applied version. Teaches the value of the pattern by showing its absence.\n      \n        \n          \n            BEFORE · coupled mess\n            stock.price = x;dashboard.refresh();notifier.notify();portfolio.recalc();analytics.track();add a new listener? touch stock\n          \n          \n            AFTER · Observer\n            stock.setPrice(x);subscribers notifiedautomatically · Stockdoesn't know about them\n          \n        \n      \n      Content: 36 before/after pairs (Opus writes). Complements existing lessons, doesn't replace. ~36 pattern × 15min drafting = 9h Opus time.","choice":"c2","id":null,"timestamp":1776644188722}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C3\n    \n      Real-world case studies · \"Netflix / Uber / Stripe uses this\"\n      Each pattern's lesson adds a \"In production\" section — short (100-200 word) case studies citing real companies. Netflix uses Circuit Breaker in Hystrix. Spotify uses Observer in RxJava. Stripe's idempotency layer uses Proxy. Connects abstract patterns to real systems users already respect.\n      \n        \n          N\n          Netflix · Circuit Breaker (Hystrix)\n        \n        \"When a downstream service fails, Hystrix's circuit breaker opens after 20 failures in 10 seconds. Netflix handles 100B+ API calls/day — without CB, one bad microservice would cascade.\"\n      \n      ~20 patterns have clean production examples (heavy-hitters). 16 more may need creative sourcing. Links to real tech blogs. Converts patterns from theoretical to \"this is how X Company scales\". Opus writes + links. ~10-12h.","choice":"c3","id":null,"timestamp":1776644197446}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C4\n    \n      Pattern genealogy graph · \"how patterns relate across the 36\"\n      A standalone page showing all 36 patterns as nodes in a force-directed graph, edges showing relationships: related-to, often-confused-with, historically-evolved-from, commonly-composed-with. Click a node → zoom in. Data already exists in your codebase (relatedPatterns, confusedWith). Just no visualization yet.\n      \n        FactoryMethod\n        \n        AbstractFactory\n        \n        Builder\n      \n      D3-force or React Flow (already in stack). ~8-12h. Data already exists from research file 02. Listed as gap in audit file 11 — finally ship it.","choice":"c4","id":null,"timestamp":1776644203111}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C5\n    \n      \"Find this pattern in the wild\" · live GitHub snippets\n      Bottom of each pattern page: curated list of 3-5 real open-source code examples using the pattern. Linked to GitHub with line numbers. \"Here's Observer in React's useReducer internals\" with highlighted snippet. Makes the pattern tangible — you can go read the actual working code.\n      \n        📁 facebook/react\n        packages/react/src/ReactHooks.js:L141-158\n        → Classical Observer implementation\n      \n      Manual curation: 36 patterns × 3 links = 108 link-line references. High signal-to-noise ratio for career engineers. ~15-20h content effort.","choice":"c5","id":null,"timestamp":1776644208700}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C6\n    \n      \"Draw from memory\" challenge · pattern as pure recall\n      Novel format: pattern page has a \"Close your eyes, open this\" button. Canvas is blank. User gets 3 minutes to drag-build the pattern from scratch — no reference, no starter. Auto-grader checks. Pass = Mastered tier bonus. Feels like a pop quiz, but voluntary.\n      Uses existing grading engine. Timer + \"no reference\" mode toggle on canvas. Spaced repetition gold — this is Anki with UML. ~6h.","choice":"c6","id":null,"timestamp":1776644211633}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C7\n    \n      Side-by-side multi-language viewer · TS / Py / Java / Go / Rust columns\n      Current design shows code as tabs (switch one at a time). Propose: optional \"compare\" view showing the same pattern in 3 languages side-by-side. See how idiomatic differences express the same intent — Python's __instance__ vs Java's synchronized. Requires adding Go + Rust snippets to the 3 existing (TS/Py/Java).\n      UI toggle: tabs → columns. Adding Go + Rust snippets for 36 patterns ≈ 8-10h Opus. UI work ≈ 4h.","choice":"c7","id":null,"timestamp":1776644212866}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C8\n    \n      Audio narration · podcast-style lesson mode\n      Each lesson gets a 5-8 min audio narration (Claude Opus voice-gen or human). \"Play audio\" button in Learn mode — canvas highlights follow narration timestamps. Perfect for commutes, bathtub, running. Turns reading into listening.\n      Audio production: 36 patterns × 6 min avg = 3.6 hours of content. AI voice gen (~$200 ElevenLabs) OR human narrator (~$2K). Timestamp alignment with canvas highlights = ~10h. Audio first-mover advantage in tech-education.","choice":"c8","id":null,"timestamp":1776644214366}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C9\n    \n      Pattern origin stories · 1-paragraph history per pattern\n      \"Who coined this? Why? When?\" Small history card per pattern: \"Erich Gamma et al. coined Observer in the 1995 Gang of Four book. Inspired by the Model-View-Controller pattern at Xerox PARC in 1979.\" Makes patterns feel like human inventions, not cosmic laws. Counter to the \"memorize 36 abstract names\" feel.\n      Opus writes: 36 × 5-min research each ≈ 3h content. ~2h UI. Small effort, big humanization.","choice":"c9","id":null,"timestamp":1776644260525}
